			<div class="post-2117 post hentry category-uncategorized post_box top" id="post-2117">
				<div class="headline_area">
					<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.cookthink.com/blog/2011/01/baby-back/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Baby Back Ribs">Baby Back Ribs</a></h2>
					<p class="headline_meta">by <span class="author vcard"><a href="http://www.cookthink.com/blog/author/brys/" class="url fn">brys</a></span> on <abbr class="published" title="2011-01-09">2011</abbr> &middot; <span><a href="http://www.cookthink.com/blog/2011/01/baby-back/#comments" rel="nofollow">0 comments</a></span></p>
				</div>
				<div class="format_text entry-content">
<p><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5285/5339575385_55d1f0427f.jpg" alt="" /></p>
<p>I&#8217;ve had these marinating for two days in a puree of shallot and ginger, plus orange marmalade, soy sauce, rice wine vinegar, chile flakes and a little peanut oil. Think I&#8217;m just going to cook them in the oven &#8212; it&#8217;s cold and damp outside. Probably gently braise them at 200f for an hour or so, then broil them at the end. Hopefully the broil will give them at least a little charred flavor.</p>
<p class="to_comments"><span class="bracket">{</span> <a href="http://www.cookthink.com/blog/2011/01/baby-back/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>0</span> comments</a> <span class="bracket">}</span></p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="post-2113 post hentry category-uncategorized post_box" id="post-2113">
				<div class="headline_area">
					<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.cookthink.com/blog/2011/01/potatoes-and-dill/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Potatoes and Dill">Potatoes and Dill</a></h2>
					<p class="headline_meta">by <span class="author vcard"><a href="http://www.cookthink.com/blog/author/brys/" class="url fn">brys</a></span> on <abbr class="published" title="2011-01-09">2011</abbr> &middot; <span><a href="http://www.cookthink.com/blog/2011/01/potatoes-and-dill/#comments" rel="nofollow">0 comments</a></span></p>
				</div>
				<div class="format_text entry-content">
<p><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5082/5339712336_89af3622d2.jpg" alt="" /></p>
<p>Who discovered that potatoes and dill were such a good match? We probably have a host of people to thank. Here we have meaty, succulent potatoes with several tart ingredients: mustard, buttermilk, vinegar and lemon &#8212; rounded out with a little olive oil, then brightened with fresh chopped dill. Even in winter, they&#8217;re begging to be chilled. I predict it keeps getting better while I get the grill ready for the ribs.</p>
<p class="to_comments"><span class="bracket">{</span> <a href="http://www.cookthink.com/blog/2011/01/potatoes-and-dill/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>0</span> comments</a> <span class="bracket">}</span></p>
				</div>
			</div>

